[2] Cholera - Namibia (Ohangwena)
Date: Tue 25 Mar 2008
Source: AllAfrica, New Era (Windhoek) report [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200803250365.html>


The number of confirmed cholera cases in the Ohangwena Region had
risen from 8 to 13 by yesterday morning [24 Mar 2008]. Oshana
Regional Health Director, Dr Naftali Hamata, told New Era yesterday
that suspected cholera cases continue to rise. By yesterday [24 Mar
2008], there were 533 suspected cases, 13 confirmed, 14 cases were
being treated in hospital and healthcare tents while deaths remained at 3.

More suspected cholera cases are being reported in flooded areas in
the north, with health officials blaming the rise on contaminated
water. The last 2 weeks saw a shortage in water purification tablets
supplies at most health centers. Health officials are expected to
distribute water purification tablets and sachets to learners at
different schools in the region.

Hydrologist Guido van Langenhove said the satellite images showed
that heavy rains were received in both Angola and Namibia during the
weekend. The report says although the rains were received over
shorter periods than before, the water levels at the 2 recording
sites between Omafu and Okalongo have shown a slight increase again.

[Byline: Petronella Sibeene]

--
Communicated by:
Sidi Coulibaly
<sidi_couly@yahoo.ca>

[A map of Namibia showing the province of Ohangwena in the north can
